@host = http://localhost:5000/api/v1

### ============ AUTH (Phase 3): the tenant comes from the token now ============

### 1. Login as the dev-seeded platform admin. Copy "accessToken" into @adminToken below.
POST {{host}}/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{ "email": "admin@platform.local", "password": "Admin123$" }

### ---- paste tokens as you collect them ----
@adminToken = PASTE_ADMIN_ACCESS_TOKEN
@staffAToken = PASTE_STAFF_A_ACCESS_TOKEN
@staffBToken = PASTE_STAFF_B_ACCESS_TOKEN

### 2. Admin creates tenant A. Copy the returned "id" into @tenantA.
POST {{host}}/tenants
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}

{ "name": "Aurora Live", "slug": "aurora-live" }

### 3. Admin creates tenant B. Copy the returned "id" into @tenantB.
POST {{host}}/tenants
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}

{ "name": "Vortex Events", "slug": "vortex-events" }

@tenantA = PASTE_TENANT_A_ID
@tenantB = PASTE_TENANT_B_ID

### 4. Admin provisions staff for tenant A, then B (change email/tenantId).
POST {{host}}/auth/register-staff
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{adminToken}}

{ "email": "staff-a@aurora.local", "password": "Staff123$", "role": "OrganizerStaff", "tenantId": "{{tenantA}}" }

### 5. Staff A logs in -> copy accessToken into @staffAToken. (Decode it at jwt.io: note the tenant_id claim.)
POST {{host}}/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{ "email": "staff-a@aurora.local", "password": "Staff123$" }

### ============ EVENTS: no tenant header anywhere - the claim drives everything ============

### 6. Staff A creates an event. Copy id into @eventA.
POST {{host}}/events
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{staffAToken}}

{ "name": "Aurora Summer Fest", "venueName": "Riverside Park", "startsAt": "2027-07-01T20:00:00Z" }

@eventA = PASTE_EVENT_A_ID

### 7. Publish it (Draft -> OnSale). Run again to see the 409 state-machine rejection.
POST {{host}}/events/{{eventA}}/publish
Authorization: Bearer {{staffAToken}}

### 8. Add a ticket type + inventory. Copy the ticket type id into @ticketTypeA.
POST {{host}}/events/{{eventA}}/ticket-types
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{staffAToken}}

{ "name": "General Admission", "price": 49.90, "currency": "EUR", "totalQuantity": 500 }

@ticketTypeA = PASTE_TICKET_TYPE_ID

### 9. THE ISOLATION KICKER: staff B (valid token, wrong tenant) reads A's event -> 404.
GET {{host}}/events/{{eventA}}
Authorization: Bearer {{staffBToken}}

### 10. Anonymous -> 401. Customer token on staff endpoints -> 403.
GET {{host}}/events

### ============ HOLDS: TTL inventory reservation ============

### 11. Reserve 3 tickets (watch availableQuantity drop in step 12). Copy hold id into @holdA.
POST {{host}}/holds
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{staffAToken}}

{ "ticketTypeId": "{{ticketTypeA}}", "quantity": 3 }

@holdA = PASTE_HOLD_ID

### 12. Event graph shows live availability.
GET {{host}}/events/{{eventA}}
Authorization: Bearer {{staffAToken}}

### 13. Release the hold (run twice: second time is a 409 - no double refund).
POST {{host}}/holds/{{holdA}}/release
Authorization: Bearer {{staffAToken}}

### ============ TOKEN LIFECYCLE ============

### 14. Refresh (paste the refreshToken from any login). Then REPLAY the same value: 401 + family revoked.
POST {{host}}/auth/refresh
Content-Type: application/json

{ "refreshToken": "PASTE_REFRESH_TOKEN" }

### 15. Customer self-registration (always Customer role - try it on staff endpoints for a 403).
POST {{host}}/auth/register
Content-Type: application/json

{ "email": "buyer@example.com", "password": "Buyer1234$" }
